//! third-eye — sovereign video-perception engine.
//!
//! See PLAN.md for the full architecture. This crate is built in phases:
//! - P0 (done): video decode lives in `frffmpeg::decode` (native host concern).
//! - P1 (done): [`cadence`] — the "as fast as the system can handle stably" governor:
//!   frf-parallel per-frame work + antiqueue corridor + a stride controller that converges
//!   on the maximum stable sample rate, degrading temporal density instead of blowing up.
//! - P2+: vision/recon, tracking, scene model, certified-knowledge CRDT, plenoramic publish.
//!
//! ## Native vs wasm32
//!
//! The perception CORE (`frame`, `vision`, `track`, `recon`, `physics`, `motion`, `knowledge`,
//! `scene`, `scene_intel`, `object_intel`, `metacog`, `prediction`, `affordance`,
//! `counterfactual`, `interaction`, `orientation_spinor`, `publish`, `pipeline`) is a pure
//! function of (RGB24 frame, prior in-memory state) → packed `ConsciousTick` bytes, and compiles
//! for `wasm32-unknown-unknown`. Three host-coupled concerns are gated out on wasm:
//!   - `cadence` — pulls `frffmpeg::Decoder` + `std::time::Instant`. The frf value-door + antiqueue
//!     governor it embodies is reused PER-FRAME by [`pipeline::PerceptionCore`] (the wasm hot path
//!     runs the same gnosis-frf certified-cost + antiqueue corridor, single-threaded serial side).
//!   - `priors::PriorSet::load` (a `std::fs` file read) — wasm callers use the always-available
//!     `priors::PriorSet::from_json` and pass the priors JSON string in via the engine opts.
//!   - the `third-eye` bin (CLI/stdin/`std::fs`/`std::process`) — not compiled for wasm.

